ram":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6J8BQqAUATApgMwEsA7HEADxAwBsCBnAF0poZAEYEBKJuxgZhAAsHYemCg8AJ2IBzUvQD2IAEakA7lPr0cRZQE8QDAK64i9dOgySZpaj3LlhQA","body":" "}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.29","id":"#ex-2.29","child":[{"body":"\n    A binary\n    \n    mobile consists of two branches, a left branch and a right\n    branch.  Each branch is a rod of a certain length, from which hangs\n    either a weight or another binary mobile.  We can represent a binary\n    mobile using compound data by constructing it from two branches (for\n    example, using ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"list"},{"body":"):\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":30,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6J8BQqAUATApgMwEsA7HEDAWwEMBrHAWnIHsAjAgG1I7wBcQAnAgHMAFtwCUqEGTYEAzry68BI8WKA","body":"(define (make-mobile left right)\n  (list left right)) "},{"body":"\n    A branch is constructed from a ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"length"},{"body":" (which\n    must be a number) together with a ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"structure"},{"body":",\n    which may be either a number (representing a simple weight) or another\n    mobile:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":31,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6J8BQqAUATApgMwEsA7HEDAWwEMBrHAWgCMAnSogYwAsQAbHIgcwAuXAM6CmAVzaCJTHAEpUIMtwJiefIaPFSZc+fKA","body":"(define (make-branch length structure)\n  (list length structure)) "},{"tag":"OL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n        Write the corresponding selectors\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"left-branch"},{"body":"\n\tand\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"right-branch"},{"body":",\n\twhich return the branches of a mobile, and\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"branch-length"},{"body":"\n\tand\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"branch-structure"},{"body":",\n\twhich return the components of a branch.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n        Using your selectors, define a\n        procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"total-weight"},{"body":"\n        that returns the total weight of a mobile.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n        A mobile is said to be\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"balanced","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":" if the torque applied by its top-left branch is equal\n\tto that applied by its top-right branch (that is, if the length of the\n\tleft rod multiplied by the weight hanging from that rod is equal to the\n\tcorresponding product for the right side) and if each of the submobiles\n\thanging off its branches is balanced. Design a predicate that tests\n\twhether a binary mobile is balanced.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n        Suppose we change the representation of mobiles so that the\n\tconstructors are\n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":32,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6J8BQqAUATApgMwEsA7HEDAWwEMBrHAWnIHsAjAgG1I7wBcQAnAgHMAFtwCUqEGQDGjIgGcQXXgJHiJmXIRJkqtOsz6Ui04UpxFB3M-O58ArtO72+OCVIyyF5y9ZC2HJxc3MSA","body":"(define (make-mobile left right)\n  (cons left right))\n\n(define (make-branch length structure)\n  (cons length structure)) "},{"body":"\n        How much do you need to change your programs to convert to the new\n        representation?\n      ","tag":"#text"}]}]}],"solution":[{"tag":"OL","child":[{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":33,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":34,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":35,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"LI","child":[{"body":"\n\t  With this alternative representation, the selector functions for\n\t  mobile and branch need to change as follows:\n\t  ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":36,"eval":false}]}]}]},{"tag":"SUBHEADING","id":"#h1","child":[{"body":"Mapping over trees","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p5","child":[{"body":"\n    Just as ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":" is a powerful abstraction for\n    dealing with sequences, ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":" together with\n    recursion is a powerful abstraction for dealing with trees.  For instance,\n    the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"scale-tree"},{"body":"procedure,\n    analogous to\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"scale-list"},{"body":"\n    of section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.2.1","href":"/sicp/2.2.1"},{"body":", takes as arguments a numeric\n    factor and a tree whose leaves are numbers.  It returns a tree of the same\n    shape, where each number is multiplied by the factor. The recursive plan\n    for\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"scale-tree"},{"body":"\n    is similar to the one for\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"count-leaves"},{"body":":","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":37,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6J8BQqAUATApgMwEsA7HEDAZwGMBDAGxwFoAXAJx1NfZD2sqYHsWASlQgylfkSxkMRAK61aAfhCccQkEQK0RYvRln8mZAA7UCLFWqEaMAKlVtSPPoJui9ZHLXKkMEonIyKjpGNXFqFkd2DRcBYQ9PJOSKGnpmJ3EsKOtuXnibQvRU0IyuDFoCcmMARjJK6oR6quMAZhAAFg0AVlsG4wA2EAB2d2TkmoAGISA","body":"(define (scale-tree tree factor)\n  (cond ((null? tree) nil)\n     ((not (pair? tree)) (* tree factor))\n     (else (cons (scale-tree (car tree) factor)\n                 (scale-tree (cdr tree) factor))))) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":38,"eval":true,"prependLength":7,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6J8BQqAUATApgMwEsA7HEDAZwGMBDAGxwFoAXAJx1NfZD2sqYHsWASlQgylfkSxkMRAK61aAfhCccQkEQK0RYvRln8mZAA7UCLFWqEaMAKlVtSPPoJui9ZHLXKkMEonIyKjpGNXFqFkd2DRcBYQ9PJOSKGnpmJ3EsKOtuXnibQvRU0IyuDFoCcmMARjJK6oR6quMAZhAAFg0AVlsG4wA2EAB2d2TkmoAGISA","body":"(scale-tree (list 1 (list 2 (list 3 4) 5) (list 6 7))\n            10) ","output":"(10 (20 (30 40) 50) (60 70))"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p6","child":[{"body":"\n    Another way to implement\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"scale-tree"},{"body":"\n    is to regard the tree as a sequence of sub-trees and use\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":".\n    We map over the sequence, scaling each sub-tree in turn, and return the\n    list of results.  In the base case, where the tree is a leaf, we simply\n    multiply by the factor:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":39,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6J8BQqAUATApgMwEsA7HEDAZwGMBDAGxwFoAXAJx1NfZD2sqYHsWASlQgyAW2oAHMrWriARlmplyAVwXM2OEWL36MBPGSnUCLAPwh1mzjtH7HqmvS1cbb0jz6DdTgwBU1hqe3LwCwkJ+jnZR6BQujHayBORMIACMKWkI2ekAzCAALEIgAKylGLSp6QBsIADscf6OGQAMQkA","body":"(define (scale-tree tree factor)\n  (map (lambda (sub-tree)\n         (if (pair? sub-tree)\n           (scale-tree sub-tree factor)\n           (* sub-tree factor)))\n       tree)) "},{"body":"\n    Many tree operations can be implemented by similar combinations of\n    sequence operations and recursion.\n  ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.30","id":"#ex-2.30","child":[{"body":"Define a procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"square-tree"},{"body":"\n    analogous to the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"square-list"},{"body":"procedure\n    of exercise ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.21","href":"/sicp/2.2.1#ex-2.21"},{"body":".  That is,\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"square-tree"},{"body":"\n    should behave as follows:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":40,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6J8BQqAUBnAjgVwEMAnAUwFoAXUk1EDAGwEssKQBGWkL7h51+OkxYgAzCAAsAShABWSZ25dewgGwgA7JK1A","body":"(square-tree\n (list 1\n       (list 2 (list 3 4) 5)\n       (list 6 7))) ","output":"(1 (4 (9 16) 25) (36 49))"},{"body":"Define ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"square-tree"},{"body":"\n    both directly (i.e., without using any higher-order\n    procedures)\n    and also by using\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":" and recursion.\n    ","tag":"#text"}],"solution":[{"body":"\n      Directly:\t  \n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":41,"eval":false},{"body":"\n      The version using ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":":\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":42,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.31","id":"#ex-2.31","child":[{"body":"\n    Abstract your answer to exercise ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.30","href":"/sicp/2.2.2#ex-2.30"},{"body":" to\n    produce a\n    procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"tree-map"},{"body":"\n    with the property that\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"square-tree"},{"body":"\n\tcould be defined as\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":43,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6J8BQrigC4CcCmeA+gLYCGADiFgPYgBGeIA7jgJZZZ4B29AniAGcsAVwAm3LOgAU4gGasujKQICOw0vgC0uAlXx4AlCCk68mspVXr8eggYNA","body":"(define (square-tree tree) (tree-map square tree)) "}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":44,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 2.32","id":"#ex-2.32","child":[{"body":"\n    We can represent a\n    \n    set as a list of distinct elements, and we can\n    represent the set of all subsets of the set as a list of lists.  For\n    example, if the set is\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(1 2 3)"},{"body":",\n    then the set of all subsets is\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"(() (3) (2) (2 3) (1) (1 3) (1 2) (1 2 3))"},{"body":".\n      \n    Complete the\n    following \n    definition of a procedure\n    that generates the set of subsets of a set and give a clear explanation of\n    why it works:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\n(define (subsets s)\n  (if (null? s)\n    (list nil)\n    (let ((rest (subsets (cdr s))))\n      (append rest (map ?? rest)))))\n      "}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":45,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=2&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiBMA6J8BQqg","body":" "},{"body":"\n      The argument starts in a similar way as the argument for the function\n      ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cc"},{"body":"\n      in section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"1.2.2","href":"/sicp/1.2.2"},{"body":": A subset either\n      contains the first element ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$e$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" of the given\n      set, or it doesn't. If it doesn't, the problem becomes strictly smaller:\n      Compute all subsets of the tail of the list that represents the given\n      set. If it does, it must result from adding ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$e$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":"\n      to a subset that doesn't contain ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"$e$","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":". In the\n      end, we need to append both lists of subsets to obtain the list of all\n      subsets.\n    ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-1","count":1,"href":"/sicp/2.2.2#footnote-link-1","child":[{"body":"The order of the first two clauses\n    in the ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cond"},{"body":" matters, since the empty list\n    satisfies ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"null?"},{"body":" and also is not a\n    pair.","tag":"#text"}]}]